<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910819-0030</DOCNO><DOCID>910819-0030.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- RasterOps Inc.:   Stock Pact Reached in May   To Buy Truevision Scuttled</HL><DATE>08/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3</SO><CO>   ROPS</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>INDUSTRIAL TECHNOLOGY andamp; PRODUCTION, QUALITY CONTROL (ITC)SOFTWARE (SOF)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)INDIANA (IND)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   RasterOps Inc., Santa Clara, Calif., said it terminatedits agreement to buy Truevision Inc., a closely held maker ofproducts used in computers for film and video production,because the companies couldn't agree on terms.   RasterOps, a maker of graphics products for desktopcomputers, had viewed the Truevision acquisition, announcedin May, as a way to enter new markets in computer graphics.But Kieth Sorenson, RasterOps's president, said &quot;itunfortunately does not appear that we will be able to reachagreement on a transaction that would be satisfactory forboth sides.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   Under the pact, RasterOps was to buy Truevision for 2.8million shares, which traded in May at $23 a share, givingthe deal a value of $64.4 million. But RasterOps's stockprice subsequently rose, leading to a disagreement overterms, said Cathleen Asch, president of Truevision,Indianapolis. &quot;We couldn't come to terms on valuation,&quot; shesaid.   RasterOps's stock fell $1.375 to close at $27.875 innational over-the-counter trading Friday.</TEXT></DOC>